AKDSFramework searching package. Implements Linear, Binary Search

AKDSFramework.applications.search.binarysearch(array: list, target: any, require_sorting=False) → any¶
Binary search implementation. Use only when your array is sorted. Pass in require_sorting as True to sort on the fly.
Args:

  • array (list): Search space

  • target (any): Value of the target that you want to search

Returns:

True if element found else False

AKDSFramework.applications.search.linearsearch(array: list, target: any) → any¶
Implementation of linear search. Use only when your array is not sorted. If you have a sorted array use binary search instead. Running time \(O(N)\)
Args:

  • array (list): List of any data type

  • target (any): Value of the target that you want to search

Returns:

None if no element found or dictionary of {index, target} of the element where it’s found

AKDSFramework.applications.singlesourceshortestpath module¶

AKDSFramework.applications.singlesourceshortestpath.compute_bellmanford(graph: AKDSFramework.structure.graph.GraphDictionaryRepresented, starting_vertex: str)¶
Computes single source shortest path algorithms using bellman ford algorithm
Args:

  • graph (GraphDictionaryRepresented): Graph you want to work on

  • starting_vertex (str): Starting Vertex of the graph to compute bellman ford

Algorithm:

  • Prepare distance and predecessor for each node

  • Relax all the edges \(|V|-1\) times

  • Run the loop one more time to check for if there is any negative edge cycle.

Time complexity:

Time complexity is \(O(V * E)\) where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges

AKDSFramework.applications.singlesourceshortestpath.compute_dijkstra(graph: AKDSFramework.structure.graph.GraphDictionaryRepresented, starting_vertex: str) → dict¶
Computes dijkstra single source shortest path algorithm. Requires GraphDictionaryRepresented dictionary build with Vertex class.
Args:

  • graph (GraphDictionaryRepresented): Graph on which you want to operate

  • starting_vertex: Starting vertex name in a string.

Time complexity:

Building distances dictionary takes \(O(V)\) time. The while loop is executed once for every entry that gets added to the priority queue (Min Heap). An entry can only be added when we explore an edge, so there are at most \(O(E)\) iterations of the while loop. The for loop is executed at most once for every vertex, since the current_distance > distances[current_vertex] check ensures that we only process a vertex once. The for loop iterates over outgoing edges, so among all iterations of the while loop, the body of the for loop executes at most \(O(E)\) times. Finally, if we consider that each priority queue operation (adding or removing an entry) is \(O(\log E)\), we can say the total running time is \(O(V + E \log E)\).

AKDSFramework.applications.string_matching module¶

Linear time string matching algorithm from Knuth, Morris and Pratt. Mathematical complexity: O(m + n), where n is the length of the sequence and m is the length of query string
